title: Request for approval to accept inert Enva ADM 19 12 12
document_type: Requests for Approval and Site Reports
metadata_json:
{"compliance_id": "10706632-bd3b-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "document_type": "Requests for Approval and Site Reports", "document_url": "https://data.epa.ie/leap/api/v1/LicenseeReturns/byid?lr_id=10706632-bd3b-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "title": "Request for approval to accept inert Enva ADM 19 12 12", "description": "Dear Mr. McCabe, 

IMS wish to request approval to accept material from the Enva/ADM farm plastic recycling plant in Lossets, Carrickmacross, Co. Monaghan. The material is soil type material which is removed from the process and is pressed as shown in the attached images. 
See below for a series of questions IMS asked of the site with corresponding answers:
1. Full company name and facility Address
Answer:
Enva Ireland Ltd.
Lossets,
Carrickmacross,
Co. Monaghan,
A81C635
2. Source site Waste Licence number and copy thereof.
Answer:
The waste facility permit number is WFP-MN-12-0001-08. See licence attached.
3. What activity and source gave rise to the material in question?
Answer:
It is sludge from an Agri plastic film washing line that has been processed through a screw press.
4. What is the original list of waste code applied to this material? I.e. What waste codes does the site accept?
Answer:
It is plastic film accepted under 02 01 04.
5. Provide an outline/description of the waste processing giving rise to the re-assigned list of waste code.
Answer:
The film is shredded down and then washed. The resulting dirt, grit, etc. is washed from the film. This process water is then treated and cleaned in a DAF waste water treatment system. The sludge taken from the DAF is processed through a screw press to dry it. This dried sludge is the waste to be removed from our site.
6. Waste haulage licence number of the proposed haulier and copy thereof.
Answer:
The haulier to be used is J Ryans.

As the material originates from a waste permitted site it has been designated code 19 12 12. The lab analysis is attached and shows the material to be inert. There is approx. 5,000 tonnes of this material generated annually. We would like to request acceptance of this We would like to request acceptance of this specifically from this source.
Best Regards,
Darren O'Reilly", "submission_date": "", "status": "Closed", "metadata": "{"licenseereturnid": "10706632-bd3b-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "type": "Requests for Approval and Site Reports", "reference": "LR094783", "subject": "Requests for Approval (RFA) and Site Reports:Other", "status": "Closed", "licenceid": "acc9e87d-7c61-e211-9eb5-0050568a69e2", "licenceprofileid": "6883afaf-4bda-4b0d-b76d-1808ed2cf9e9", "datereceived": "2025-05-28T00:00:00", "closeddate": "2025-06-23T00:00:00", "title": "Request for approval to accept inert Enva ADM 19 12 12", "doctype": "Requests for Approval (RFA) and Site Reports", "docsubtype": "Other", "decision": "Assessed", "description": "Dear Mr. McCabe, \r\n\r\nIMS wish to request approval to accept material from the Enva/ADM farm plastic recycling plant in Lossets, Carrickmacross, Co. Monaghan. The material is soil type material which is removed from the process and is pressed as shown in the attached images. \r\nSee below for a series of questions IMS asked of the site with corresponding answers:\r\n1. Full company name and facility Address\r\nAnswer:\r\nEnva Ireland Ltd.\r\nLossets,\r\nCarrickmacross,\r\nCo. Monaghan,\r\nA81C635\r\n2. Source site Waste Licence number and copy thereof.\r\nAnswer:\r\nThe waste facility permit number is WFP-MN-12-0001-08. See licence attached.\r\n3. {"compliance_id": "af06d6c6-db3b-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "document_type": "Incident", "document_url": "https://data.epa.ie/leap/api/v1/Incident/byid?incident_id=af06d6c6-db3b-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "title": "", "description": "Following a series of elevated COD concentrations entering the WWTP system over the course of the last few weeks, the clarifier settling has disimproved drastically. COD results for the outlet (DP001) on site have been gradually increasing as the system struggles to effectively treat the incoming loadings. Yesterday, 27th of May, the outlet sample results returned with a COD at 1200 mg/l and a SS concentration of 1020 mg/l. Today, 28th of May, the outlet sample results have returned with a COD of 1064 mg/l and SS at 940 mg/l. The corresponding COD loading was 157 kg on the 27th and 182 kg on the 28th. The SS loading was 133 kg on the 27th and 148 kg on the 28th. Since yesterday, every effort is being taken to resume the settlement in the clarifier.", "submission_date": "", "status": "Closed", "metadata": "{\"incidentid\": \"af06d6c6-db3b-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a\", \"type\": \"Incident\", \"reference\": \"INCI030402\", \"subject\": \"Breach of ELV\", \"status\": \"Closed\", \"licenceid\": \"4ec5e87d-7c61-e211-9eb5-0050568a69e2\", \"licenceprofileid\": \"177d9576-1c1f-4a4e-98b7-7babe9cdf8b2\", \"complianceinvestigationid\": null, \"incidentcategory\": \"1. Minor\", \"nature\": \"Breach of ELV\", \"vulnerablereceptors\": \"N/A as WW outfall flows to Carrigrennan for further treatment.\", \"receptors\": \"Sewer\", \"likelihoodofreoccurence\": \"High\", \"likelycause\": \"Shock load to the WWTP\", \"newrecurring\": \"Recurring\", \"datenotified\": \"2025-05-28T00:00:00\", \"closeddate\": \"2025-06-16T00:00:00\", \"approximatestart\": \"2025-05-27T08:00:00\", \"firstnoticed\": \"2025-05-27T08:00:00\", \"finishtime\": \"2025-06-06T08:00:00\", \"notifiedparties\": \"\", \"dischargepoint\": \"Yes\", \"emissionpointname\": \"P0017-DP 001\", \"uncontrolledrelease\": \"n/a\", \"description\": \"Following a series of elevated COD concentrations entering the WWTP system over the course of the last few weeks, the clarifier settling has disimproved drastically. COD results for the outlet (DP001) on site have been gradually increasing as the system struggles to effectively treat the incoming loadings. Yesterday, 27th of May, the outlet sample results returned with a COD at 1200 mg/l and a SS concentration of 1020 mg/l. Today, 28th of May, the outlet sample results have returned with a COD of 1064 mg/l and SS at 940 mg/l. The corresponding COD loading was 157 kg on the 27th and 182 kg on the 28th. The SS loading was 133 kg on the 27th and 148 kg on the 28th. Since yesterday, every effort is being taken to resume the settlement in the clarifier.\", \"otherrelevantinformation\": \"Irish water has been informed of these exceedances by email.\", \"impactonenvironment\": \"The effects of this incident on the environment are minimal as the outfall at DP001 travels for further treatment at Carrigrennan WWTP. \\r\\nOn 29th of May, results have come back OOS for COD however SS are at 504 mg/l. Results show that COD and SS for the outlet are trending downwards.\\r\\nAs of Friday 6th of June, settlement has resumed in the clarifier and additional dewatering has resulted in outlet samples being within specification of ELVs. All results from the 29th of May onward have been within the licensed ELVs.\", \"activityinprogress\": \"Normal operations were occurring at time of incident. Since the incident, flows to the wastewater have been limited. Settlement tests are being conducted to assess what additives will help resume flocculation and settling. The high COD loadings are still working their way through the system and due to this it is likely that we will have more OOS results in the coming days. \", \"dischargedetails\": null}"}

title: Request for Time Extension - Report
metadata_json:
{"compliance_id": "24146e0c-ad3b-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "document_type": "Site Updates/Notifications", "document_url": "https://data.epa.ie/leap/api/v1/LicenseeReturns/byid?lr_id=24146e0c-ad3b-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "title": "Request for Time Extension - Report ", "description": "Dear Ellen Brogan, 

As part of Site Visit Report SV31819, Section 4.3 requested that Bord na Mona Recycling Ltd submit a report detailing the findings of the below, as a  licensee return via EDEN within two months of the date of issue of this report :

1. review the groundwater monitoring results and confirm if natural attenuation is occurring; and
2. conduct trend analysis for groundwater monitoring results and include a projection as to when Groundwater Threshold Values are likely to be met for all parameters.

Our consultant has requested additional time to complete this report and has provided us with a date of 30th July 2025 for completion -  as they as currently working during a very busy period. 

Kind Regards, 
Mary Bannon
Environmental Officer
087 6846448

A faulty remote I/O drop adapter on PLC #2 for block 7 & 8 was intermittently causing faults resulting in reduced aeration treatment on block 7. Flows were low at the time. The faulty I/O module was replaced with a in stock spare on 25/05/2025, once it had been identified and treatment returned to normal. There are two additional units now on order. title: P0698-01 Honeywell - AEMP batch scheduling
metadata_json:
{"compliance_id": "017fe088-d73b-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "document_type": "Site Updates/Notifications", "document_url": "https://data.epa.ie/leap/api/v1/LicenseeReturns/byid?lr_id=017fe088-d73b-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "title": "P0698-01 Honeywell - AEMP batch scheduling", "description": "Dear Martina,

Further to our phone conversation today please be advised the following production areas, and the air emission points associated with them, are scheduled to run uninterrupted up to the Annual Shutdown planned to begin on Monday, 28th July 2025:

Root Coat - Extractor - A2-1 to A2-3 (TOC, Antimony, Lead),
Cleanline - Scrubber - A2-9 (Fluorine[HF], Nitric Acid[HNO3], Sulphuric Acid[H2SO4]),
Forge - Scrubber - A2-11 (Particulates, Nickel, Iron, Titanium).

Our preference would be for the air emission monitoring team to carry out the air monitoring between 8:00am and 4:00pm, however the operations run on the two shifts rota: 6:00am to 2:00pm and 2:00pm to 10:00pm.
If you have any more queries, please feel free to contact me.

Kind Regards,
Bart Zdrojowy
HSE Site Lead", "submission_date": "", "status": "Closed", "metadata": "{"licenseereturnid": "017fe088-d73b-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "type": "Site Updates/Notifications", "reference": "LR094796", "subject": "Site Updates/Notifications:Other", "status": "Closed", "licenceid": "cec7e87d-7c61-e211-9eb5-0050568a69e2", "licenceprofileid": "07d94887-aa7a-4a91-93a6-f414d2364fbb", "datereceived": "2025-05-28T00:00:00", "closeddate": "2025-05-30T00:00:00", "title": "P0698-01 Honeywell - AEMP batch scheduling", "doctype": "Site Updates/Notifications", "docsubtype": "Other", "decision": "Assessed", "description": "Dear Martina,\r\n\r\nFurther to our phone conversation today please be advised the following production areas, and the air emission points associated with them, are scheduled to run uninterrupted up to the Annual Shutdown planned to begin on Monday, 28th July 2025:\r\n\r\nRoot Coat - Extractor - A2-1 to A2-3 (TOC, Antimony, Lead),\r\nCleanline - Scrubber - A2-9 (Fluorine[HF], Nitric Acid[HNO3], Sulphuric Acid[H2SO4]),\r\nForge - Scrubber - A2-11 (Particulates, Nickel, Iron, Titanium).\r\n\r\nOur preference would be for the air emission monitoring team to carry out the air monitoring between 8:00am and 4:00pm, however the operations run on the two shifts rota: 6:00am to 2:00pm and 2:00pm to 10:00pm.\r\nIf you have any more queries, please feel free to contact me.\r\n\r\nKind Regards,\r\nBart Zdrojowy\r\nHSE Site Lead", "documentcategory": null, "complianceinvestigationid": null}"}

{"compliance_id": "d100aefb-473a-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "document_type": "Non Compliance", "document_url": "https://data.epa.ie/leap/api/v1/NonCompliance/byid?nc_id=d100aefb-473a-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "title": "", "description": "Incident reference INCI030340 refers.

Results of digestate quality analysis for a sample taken in April 2025 indicate that digestate after the anaerobic digestion phase did not comply with the Maximum Metal Concentration Limit set out in the EPA Licence as follows:

- Copper: 201 mg/kg DM vs the Maximum Metal Concentration Limit of 150 mg/kg DM; and
- Zinc: 593 mg/kg DM vs the Maximum Metal Concentration Limit of 400 mg/kg DM

{"compliance_id": "da1a4c4c-dd22-4c43-84f9-84b7e567893e", "document_type": "Meeting", "document_url": "https://data.epa.ie/leap/api/v1/MeetingCorrespondence/meetingbyid?meeting_id=da1a4c4c-dd22-4c43-84f9-84b7e567893e", "title": "", "description": "", "submission_date": "", "status": "Closed", "metadata": "{\"meetingid\": \"da1a4c4c-dd22-4c43-84f9-84b7e567893e\", \"type\": \"Meeting\", \"reference\": \"MTG000746\", \"subject\": \"Ringsend WWTP upgrade project update from Uisce \\u00c9ireann\", \"status\": \"Closed\", \"meetingdate\": \"2025-04-07T00:00:00\", \"organisationid\": \"f5545f77-3749-e211-9eb5-0050568a69e2\", \"location\": \"Online MS Teams\", \"regarding\": \"Compliance Investigations\", \"meetingtime\": \"12:00\", \"attendeesepa\": \"Lorcan Farrell, Stephen McCarthy, David Shannon\", \"attendeesnoepa\": \"Uisce \\u00c9ireann: Ringsend WWTP Upgrade Project Team, Compliance Team & Asset Operations\\n\", \"actionitems\": \"

A video conference meeting was held between the EPA and Uisce Éireann (UÉ) on 08/04/2025 from 12:00 to 12:50 approx.

\\n

During the meeting UÉ gave an update to the EPA on the phased upgrades being undertaken at Ringsend WWTP and a summary of treatment plant performance for Q1 2025.

\\n

Works on Hybrid II upgrades and sludge treatment facilities are progressing as scheduled with all primary aspects of the upgrade project due for completion by end 2025. A programme of ancillary works connected with the overall upgrade project is also being progressed with most completion dates falling within 2025.

\\n

A summary of plant performance was given. UÉ are aiming for 104 compliance samples to be taken during 2025. 10 no. samples records were recorded in the Q1 Update under compliance investigation (CI000025).  Compliance results were unavailable for the first three weeks of January. This was attributed to operational reasons (plant shutdowns) and management changeover. It is UÉ’s intention to make up the shortfall to 104 compliance samples over the year. It was acknowledged that there is a risk that TN and TP average limits may not be achieved this year. UÉ expect that performance will improve across all parameters once remaining upgraded SBR blocks come back on-line and as average air temperatures increase through the year. UÉ confirmed that higher than expected load on the plant (2.17 PE in 2024) was expected to continue increasing in 2025 and is also affecting treatment performance. Issues with the aeration system in the Capital Upgrade treatment block were also cited as a compounding factor in treatment performance and should be resolved by end April 2025.

\\n

The EPA instructed Uisce Éireann to carry out all actions necessary to comply with the waste water discharge licence.

\", \"licenceid\": \"4ab24fc5-2bf8-4aa8-ad9e-f4f68c559186\", \"originalmeetingid\": \"0d83b2ed-7614-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a\", \"organisationname\": \"Uisce \\u00c9ireann\"}"}
